programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: From 1990: San Francisco vs. Denver in Super Bowl XXIV in New Orleans. The 49ers cruised 55-10 to capture their second-straight title. QB Joe Montana earned MVP honors for the third time after going 22-for-29 for 297 yards and 5 TDs.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXV: Giants vs. Bills
programme.desc: From 1991: New York Giants vs. Buffalo in Super Bowl XXV in Tampa. The Giants won 20-19. Buffalo's Scott Norwood missed a 47-yard field goal with seconds remaining.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXVI: Redskins vs. Bills
programme.desc: From 1992: Buffalo vs. Washington in Super Bowl XXVI in Minneapolis. The Redskins rode Mark Rypien's arm to a 37-24 win. Rypien threw for 292 yards and 2 TDs.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXVII: Cowboys vs. Bills
programme.desc: From 1993: Dallas vs. Buffalo in Super Bowl XXVII in Pasadena, Cal. The Cowboys turned nine turnovers into 35 points in a 52-17 rout over Buffalo. Troy Aikman threw 4 TD passes and Buffalo lost its third-straight Super Bowl.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXVIII: Cowboys vs. Bills
programme.desc: From 1994: Dallas vs. Buffalo in Super Bowl XXVIII in Atlanta. This rematch of Super Bowl XXVII was won by Dallas 30-13, as the Bills lost their fourth-straight Super Bowl. Emmitt Smith ran for 132 yards and 2 TDs.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.desc: From 1995: San Francisco vs. San Diego in Super Bowl XXIX in Miami. Steve Young threw for 6 TDs and 325 yards as the 49ers prevailed 49-26 to win their fifth Super Bowl title.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXX: Steelers vs. Cowboys
programme.desc: From 1996: Pittsburgh vs. Dallas in Super Bowl XXX in Tempe, Ariz. The Cowboys struck early and often to win 27-13, scoring on their first three possessions. Larry Brown intercepted two Pittsburgh passes in the second half.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXXI: Packers vs. Patriots
programme.desc: From 1997: New England vs. Green Bay in Super Bowl XXXI in New Orleans. The Packers topped New England 35-21. Desmond Howard scored on a 99-yard kickoff return and earned MVP honors.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXXII: Broncos vs. Packers
programme.desc: From 1998: Denver vs. Green Bay in Super Bowl XXXII in San Diego. John Elway earned his long-awaited first championship by leading the Broncos to a 31-24 win. Terrell Davis ran for 3 TDs and 157 yards.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXXIII: Broncos vs. Falcons
programme.desc: From 1999: Denver vs. Atlanta in Super Bowl XXXIII in Miami. Denver won 34-19 as John Elway threw for 336 yards and a touchdown and ran for another score in his final game before retiring.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXXIV: Rams vs. Titans
programme.desc: From 2000: Tennessee vs. St. Louis in Super Bowl XXXIV in Atlanta. The Rams won their first title with a 23-16 win over Tennessee. MVP QB Kurt Warner threw for 414 yards and 2 TDs.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXXV: Ravens vs. Giants
programme.desc: From 2001: Baltimore vs. New York Giants in Super Bowl XXXV in Tampa. The Ravens' defense paved the way for a 34-7 victory. Baltimore allowed just 152 yards, forced five turnovers and had four sacks.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXXVI: Rams vs. Patriots
programme.desc: From 2002: New England vs. St. Louis in Super Bowl XXXVI in New Orleans. The Patriots won 20-17 on Adam Vinatieri's 48-yard field goal as time expired.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXXVII: Buccaneers vs. Raiders
programme.desc: From 2003: Tampa Bay vs. Oakland in Super Bowl XXXVII in San Diego. The Bucs romped to a 48-21 victory after returning 3 INTs for TDs and recording five sacks. Dwight Smith was named MVP with 2 TDs on INT returns.

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights
programme.sub-title: Super Bowl XXXVIII: Patriots vs. Panthers

programme.title: Super Bowl Highlights

For 11 years (10 in the Top 20), the show deftly blended sharp, thoughtful humor with moving scenes of dedicated, stressed doctors trying to save lives---while clinging to their own sanity---in a Mobile Army Surgical Hospital.

programme.title: Bonanza
programme.desc: Ben Cartwright and his three sons (by three wives) ride herd over the sprawling Ponderosa spread in 1860s Nevada in one of the most handsomely mounted and beloved series of all time. The first TV Western to be shown in color, it ran for 14 seasons; was the top-rated show for three of them (1964-65, '65-66 and '66-67); had a number of first-rank directors (including Robert Altman) work on some episodes; and inspired several 'Bonanza' TV-movies (none especially distinctive).

programme.title: Gunsmoke
programme.desc: This landmark adult Western centered on Marshal Matt Dillon of Dodge City. John Wayne turned down the lead, suggesting James Arness (who remained for its entire run). Originating on radio (with William Conrad as Dillon), it moved to TV in September 1955. Its popularity spawned a number of copycats, but none would enjoy the longevity (and few the consistent quality) of this classic.

programme.title: The Andy Griffith Show
programme.desc: Gentle humor and genuinely likable characters made Mayberry a beloved fixture on the TV landscape. A Top 10 hit throughout its eight-year run (it went out at No. 1), this low-key, down-home sitcom harkened back to a simpler time and place. Mayberry may be a state of mind, but the sunny optimism and simple virtues it represents have actually been set in stone--in a Raleigh, N.C., statue depicting Sheriff Andy Taylor and his son, Opie. '[The show's] central theme was love,' Griffith said.
